I have a document and an object below:

 
{code:java}
{
 "_id" : ObjectId("5c7642f49bd4e700332e82ea"),
 "name" : "Favorite",
 "reg" : /^L0F1[a-zA-Z0-9]*$/m
}
{code}
 
{code:java}
type Test struct {
  ID   primitive.ObjectID `bson:"_id,omitempty" json:"id"`
  Name string             `bson:"name,omitempty" json:"name"`
}{code}
 

When I unmarshal the document to my object, I got {{{color:#de350b}attempted to read bytes of unknown BSON type invalid{color} error.}}

There is a problem in the Distinct function. If the filter is nil, the distinct will not be executed:
{code:java}
collection.Distinct(context.Background(), "foo.bar", nil)
{code}
As a workaround I have used a blank search request:
{code:java}
collection.Distinct(context.Background(), "foo.bar", bson.D{}){code}

I declare schemas. For example:
{code:golang}
type Embedded struct {
  Name string `bson:"name"`
}

type Main struct {
  Embedded
  OtherField int64 `bson:"otherField"`
}
{code}
When I try to load an instance of {{Main}} structure from the database, e.g.:
{code:golang}
cursor, err := client.Database("my").Collection("myColl").Find(context.TODO(), bsonD{})

if err != nil {
 return err
}

for cursor.Next(context.TODO()) {
  var m Main
  if err := cursor.Decode(&m); err != nil {
    return err
  }

  fmt.Printf("name=\"%s\"\n", m.Name) // outputs `name=""`
}
{code}

Fields having 3 characters are not stored:
{code:java}
...
type CheckResults struct { 
  domain string
  rct    string
  rst    string
  stt    string
  spt    string
  rsc    int
  rsm    string
}
...

func main() {
...
    PostResults := CheckResults{"domain.tld", "rct-example", "rst-example", "stt-example", "spt-example", 100, "rsm-example"}
...
}{code}
This will create (in my code) a collection, a document but no fields and data, not even for "domain".

If I do change the length of these for example DomainName, RecordTime and so on the data will get stored.

When parsing relaxed extended JSON with a date string, the code in [https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-go-driver/blob/master/bson/bsonrw/extjson_wrappers.go#L206] uses the UnixNano function ([https://golang.org/pkg/time/#Time.UnixNano]) which can't represent dates after the year 2262. 

This can be changed to
{code:java}
t.Unix()*1e3 + t.Nanosecond()/1e6{code}
instead.

Calling {{Decode}} twice on a {{SingleResult}} gives {{ErrNoDocument}} on the second invocation.  This may be surprising to users, as there's no reason why decoding a result shouldn't be idempotent, so this should either be fixed or clearly documented.

Test program:
{noformat}
package main

import (
	"context"
	"fmt"
	"log"

	"go.mongodb.org/mongo-driver/bson"
	"go.mongodb.org/mongo-driver/bson/primitive"
	"go.mongodb.org/mongo-driver/mongo"
)

type X struct {
	ID   primitive.ObjectID `bson:"_id,omitempty"`
	Name string             `bson:"name"`
}

func main() {
	ctx := context.Background()

	client, err := mongo.Connect(ctx)
	if err != nil {
		log.Fatal(err)
	}

	coll := client.Database("test").Collection("decodeit")
	_ = coll.Drop(ctx)

	doc := X{Name: "hello world"}
	res, err := coll.InsertOne(ctx, doc)
	if err != nil {
		log.Fatal(err)
	}
	id := res.InsertedID
	fmt.Println("Inserted", id)

	got := coll.FindOne(ctx, bson.D{{"_id", id}})
	if got.Err() != nil {
		log.Fatal(got.Err())
	}

	var doc2 X
	err = got.Decode(&doc2)
	if err != nil {
		log.Fatalf("doc2 %v", err)
	}
	fmt.Println("Doc2", doc2)

	var doc3 X
	err = got.Decode(&doc3)
	if err != nil {
		log.Fatalf("doc3 %v", err)
	}
	fmt.Println("Doc3", doc3)
}
{noformat}

